The Department shall prepare fishery management plans for the following species:
Striped bass or rockfish;
White perch;
Yellow perch;
American shad;
Hickory shad;
Oysters;
Blue crabs;
Bluefish;
Herring;
Weakfish;
Croaker;
Spot;
Summer flounder;
American eel;
Red drum;
Black drum;
Spotted sea trout;
Horseshoe crabs;
Menhaden;
Tautog;
Black sea bass;
Scup;
Hard shell clams; and
Catfish.

The Department may prepare fishery management plans for any species of fish if, after consultation with the Tidal Fisheries Advisory Commission and the Sport Fisheries Advisory Commission, the Department determines that the plans are necessary based on:
The population of the species;
The distribution of the species;
The habitat needs of the species; or
Other biological, ecological, or socioeconomic factors concerning the species.

section.section:
Conservation and management measures adopted under a fishery management plan, to the extent possible:
Shall prevent overfishing while attempting to achieve the best and most efficient utilization of the State's fishery resources;
Shall be based on the best information available;
May not discriminate unfairly among groups of fishermen or have economic allocation as its sole purpose;
Shall take into account and allow for variations among, and contingencies in, fisheries, fishery resources, and catches; and
Shall avoid duplication of regulatory efforts and unnecessary costs to the State and to any other person.

Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, a fishery management plan may apply separately or jointly to the waters of the Chesapeake Bay and its tidal tributaries, the coastal bays and their tributaries, and the Maryland waters of the Atlantic Ocean and shall include:
The best available estimates of sustainable harvest rates;
Indicators that would trigger any tightening or loosening of harvest restrictions;
A description of the fishery, including:
The history of the fishery, and its current condition relative to historic populations;
The numbers of potential commercial and recreational fishermen projected to participate in the fishery;
The type and quantity of fishing gear used commercially;
Where practicable, the cost likely to be incurred in the management of the fishery; and
The actual and potential revenues from the recreational and commercial fishery;
If the Department determines that a fishery has been, or is currently, overfished:
A species-specific time period for:
A description of:
Other pertinent data that will assist the Secretary in determining conservation and management measures reasonably necessary to ensure that the fishery resources will be sustained.

The Department may waive the requirements in paragraph (1)(iv) of this subsection for a species of fish if the Department determines that meeting the requirements is not practicable or biologically appropriate based on:
The specific biology of the species;
The management of the species under a federal or multi-state fishery management plan;
The designation of the species as a nuisance;
Environmental conditions; or
Other ecological factors.
